{"ADUs": {
"MainClaim": {
"type": "MajorClaim",
"text": "Badiou and Meillassoux dissociate themselves from the Heideggerian hermeneutics of finitude and adopt mathematics as their basic ontological model, leading to a contemporary version of atheism (Badiou) or the reintroduction of a divine entity (Meillassoux)"
},
"Untitled 1": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger's critique of ontotheology is not limited to the metaphysical models in which the metaphysical or Christian God holds an absolute position"
},
"Untitled 2": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger views Nietzsche as a culmination of ontotheological thinking"
},
"Untitled 3": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The ontotheological hierarchy implicit in Kant's critical philosophy is absolutized in speculative idealism"
},
"Untitled 4": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger's notion of ontotheology is not limited to the metaphysical models in which the metaphysical or Christian God holds an absolute position"
},
"Untitled 5": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger's later thinking, the'other beginning' of Western thought, would transform the first (Greek) beginning(s) of philosophy and metaphysics into a post-Nietzschean and post-metaphysical approach"
},
"Untitled 6": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger's postmetaphysical divinity is neither a'being' nor an'non-being,' but a dimension of transcendence that resists objectification"
},
"Untitled 7": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Heidegger's postmetaphysical thinking makes both of the former points of reference interdependent dimensions or poles in a multidimensional and multipolar event of the spatiotemporal contextualization of meaningful presence"
},
"Untitled 8": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Badiou's contemporary atheism is a break with the Heideggerian hermeneutics of finitude"
},
"Untitled 9": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Badiou's mathematical, set-theoretical ontology accepts only consistent multiplicities and rejects the notion of an ultimate and absolute unity"
},
"Untitled 10": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's speculative materialism is a genuine system that deduces all of its elements from its fundamental principle, namely, that of absolute contingency"
},
"Untitled 11": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's refutation of ontotheology is an independent direct consequence of the principle of contingency"
},
"Untitled 12": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's philosophy is a speculative materialism that claims access to some form of absolute, but not metaphysical, being"
},
"Untitled 13": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's notion of a God-entity is a merely possible and contingent one"
},
"Untitled 14": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's divinity is not to be confused with the'God who may be' of Richard Kearney's account"
},
"Untitled 15": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's'God to come' is'possible' in the Deleuzian sense of virtuality"
},
"Untitled 16": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's divinity is a possibility that is in no way foreshadowed or implied by what precedes it, but can only emerge ex nihilo"
},
"Untitled 17": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's divinity is not to be confused with the emergence of life from the world of matter and to the emergence of thought from the world of biological life"
},
"Untitled 18": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's divinity is a notion of a divine'advent,' of the possible coming-into-presence of the divine in a purely contingent and virtual, unmotivated and unpredictable, but nonetheless concrete and intratemporal, event"
},
"Untitled 19": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's divinity can bestow a purpose and dimension to the present situation in the form of an unfounded but rationally legitimate hope"
},
"Untitled 20": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The contemporary philosophical overcoming of ontotheology has left us with the fundamental figure of a non-present and purely futural god"
},
"Untitled 21": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The hermeneutical approach basically insisted on conceiving this god-to-come as a dimension of purely potential futurity"
},
"Untitled 22": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The recent speculative developments of contemporary materialism have resuscitated a genuinely messianic notion of a divine'advent,' of the possible coming-into-presence of the divine in a purely contingent and virtual, unmotivated and unpredictable, but nonetheless concrete and intratemporal, event"
},
"Untitled 23": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Meillassoux's forthcoming works and their philosophical reception will determine whether the'strong correlationist' phase in philosophical approaches to theology is truly giving way to a new, non-ontotheological rationalism"
},
"Untitled 24": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The contemporary philosophical overcoming of ontotheology has led to the reintroduction of an explicitly philosophical notion of God as a being/entity, but one that is no longer the ontotheological necessary being but a merely possible and contingent one"
},
"Untitled 25": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The fundamental figure of a non-present and purely futural god has emerged in contemporary philosophy"
},
