{"ADUs": {
"MainClaim": {
"type": "MajorClaim",
"text": "The demise of classical neo-Kantianism between the wars had at least as much to do with institutional, psychological, and/or political developments as with any strictly philosophical failures."
},
"Neo-Kantianism as scapegoat": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Neo-Kantianism became the scapegoat for many of the perceived problems in imperial and Weimar culture, despite its affinities with the interwar Zeitgeist."
},
"Affinities between neo-Kantian philosophy and the interwar Zeitgeist": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Neo-Kantianism had affinities with the antimetaphysical and politically benign impulses of the interwar period, including its view that philosophy is a handmaiden to natural science and its restriction of the Geisteswissenschaften to the more amorphous realms of culture."
},
"Wholesale collapse of neo-Kantianism": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Despite its apparent affinities with the interwar Zeitgeist, neo-Kantianism suffered catastrophic collapse between the wars."
},
"Possible explanations for the collapse of neo-Kantianism": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The collapse of neo-Kantianism may be attributed to institutional, psychological, or political factors, including a natural tendency among young philosophers to seek recognition for starting something new, a new hunger for metaphysical speculation, or political hostility towards neo-Kantians."
},
"Lukacs' critique of Kant": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Lukacs' critique of Kant's philosophy as the most radical and advanced consciousness of the early bourgeoisie does not apply very well to Kant himself, even if it applies to some neo-Kantians."
},
"Kant's own views on the limits of critical reason": {
"type": "Premise",
"text": "Kant expresses awareness of the limits of theoretical knowledge and frustration with that fact."
},
"Lukacs' criticism of Kant's moral philosophy": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "Lukacs' criticism of Kant's moral philosophy as defending the individualism of the new class subject and allowing the loss of substantive freedom does not apply very well to Kant himself."
},
"New movement back to Kant": {
"type": "Claim",
"text": "The powerful attacks on Kant in the interwar period led to a new and somewhat more careful historical and philosophical study of Kant's works."
},
"MainClaim": {
"type": "MajorClaim",
"text": "The demise of classical neo-Kantianism between the wars had at least as much to do with institutional, psychological, and/or political developments as with any strictly philosophical failures."
}
},
